        {
            "id": "4fff6037c02f4742b80f4",
            "questionText": "A bowling ball, modeled as a sphere with a mass $!$M = 7\\,\\text{kg}$!$ and a radius $!$R = 0.1\\,\\text{m}$!$, rolls without slipping down a bowling lane. Its center of mass travels at a linear velocity of $!$v = 4\\,\\text{m/s}$!$. Determine the magnitude of its angular momentum.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "a7bbd4a773d9487db40bd",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling the expression for the moment of inertia of a sphere. Please choose the correct formula for the moment of inertia of a solid sphere.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f6586b7d-c0fe-4287-91e9-f20de7e236bd"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{2} M R^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{2}{5} M R^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = M R^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "9747aded9970469bad7a2",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, since the ball rolls without slipping, there is a specific relationship between its linear speed and its angular speed. Identify the correct relation connecting $!$v$!$ and $!$\\omega$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "daaa4850-76fd-458c-99ae-480cec59b41f"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = v \\cdot R$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = \\frac{v}{R}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = \\frac{R}{v}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c04b590a7e9a496299a31",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the correct moment of inertia formula and the given values $!$M = 7\\,\\text{kg}$!$ and $!$R = 0.1\\,\\text{m}$!$, calculate the moment of inertia of the bowling ball. Enter the numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.028"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m\u00b2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f6586b7d-c0fe-4287-91e9-f20de7e236bd"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ffaf145223a74a34bc7e7",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Next, calculate the angular velocity using the relation from the previous step with the given linear speed $!$v = 4\\,\\text{m/s}$!$ and $!$R = 0.1\\,\\text{m}$!$. Compute its value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "40"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "daaa4850-76fd-458c-99ae-480cec59b41f"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "b9d78d50cbe9476e8c17c",
                    "stepText": "Finally, now that you have both the moment of inertia and the angular velocity, use them to determine the angular momentum of the bowling ball. Compute the final numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.12"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m\u00b2/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2b9428ca-8d6d-4190-afd1-29f6d9298536",
                        "f6586b7d-c0fe-4287-91e9-f20de7e236bd"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "a9898a38b9454a198f907",
            "questionText": "A seesaw, which is a uniform plank of length $!$L = 4\\,\\text{m}$!$ and mass $!$M = 10\\,\\text{kg}$!$, is pivoted at its center. A child with a mass $!$m_1 = 30\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits at one end of the plank. Another child, with a mass $!$m_2 = 20\\,\\text{kg}$!$, sits $!$1\\,\\text{m}$!$ from the opposite end. If the seesaw is released from rest, calculate the initial angular acceleration of the seesaw about the pivot point.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "98b4049b54de4be890454",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the distances from the pivot for each child. Given that the plank is 4 m long and pivoted at its center, what are the distances from the pivot for the child at the end and the child sitting 1 m from the opposite end?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "r1 = 2, r2 = 1"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "27831cd627bb4d3aa5de1",
                    "stepText": "Now, to compute the individual torques exerted by each child, we need to select the correct formula for torque. Which among the following formulas correctly represents torque in this context?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = m g r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = m r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = m g$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "061476c4e19b4c2e9cbf1",
                    "stepText": "After computing the torques for each child and finding the net torque, we move on to determining the moment of inertia of the seesaw system. First, for the uniform plank pivoted about its center, which formula correctly gives its moment of inertia?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{12}ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{3}ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6e4dd0e6a6544d318cab7",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that we have the formula for the rod, compute the total moment of inertia by summing the contribution of the plank and the contributions of the children (modeled as point masses). What value do you obtain for the total moment of inertia?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "153.33"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\\,m^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "5e52091733a04316af7a1",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need to relate the net torque and the moment of inertia to angular acceleration. Which equation correctly establishes this relationship in rotational dynamics?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b2a38ec-ad3c-4fda-9fed-c1f652dea80e"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\frac{\\tau}{I}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\frac{I}{\\tau}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\tau \\, I$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "24e28c64679b4c91bb574",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the net torque you computed earlier and the total moment of inertia from the previous step, calculate the initial angular acceleration of the seesaw. What numerical value do you get?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2.55"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b2a38ec-ad3c-4fda-9fed-c1f652dea80e"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
